Dry N-CD were dispersed in a mixture containing n-butanol (4.7 mL), methanol (340 μL) and chloroform (340 μL) using an ultrasonic bath. The dispersions were filtered using a syringe with a PVDF membrane filter (Millipore®, 0.45 µm). Finally, the ZnO nanoparticles were dispersed in this mixture using an ultrasonic bath for 30 min (sample designated as ZnO/N-CD(2%)). A ZnO dispersion was also prepared in the absence of N-CD [44,45]. Dispersions containing different relative amounts of N-CD, namely ZnO/N-CD(0.1%), ZnO/N-CD(0.25%), ZnO/N-CD(0.5%) and ZnO/N-CD(1%), were prepared by combining adequate amounts of ZnO/N-CD(2%) and ZnO dispersions (see Fig. S1, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). All the resulting dispersions were stirred and filtered through a PVDF membrane filter (Millipore®, 0.45 µm) before use.

The composition of the N-CD powder was further evaluated through the XPS spectra (see Fig. S2, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). The XPS survey spectrum of the N-CD showed three typical peaks at 285.2, 532.2 and 400.2 eV, indicating the presence of carbon (C1s, 67.9 %), oxygen (O1s, 15.5 %) and nitrogen (N1s, 16.6 %) elements, respectively, on the surface. As shown in Fig. S2b, the high-resolution XPS spectrum of C1s can be fitted into three components at 284.2, 286.1 and 288.1 eV, which correspond to C=C/C−C, C−O/C−N and C=O/C=N bonds, respectively. The high-resolution XPS spectrum of O1s (Fig. S2c) showed a component at 531.9 eV related to hydroxyl groups (C−OH) and another component with lower intensity at 534.1 eV associated to carbonyl groups (C=O). The high-resolution XPS spectrum of N1s (Fig. S2d) revealed the presence of pyridinic type (398.8 eV), pyrrolic type (399.8 eV) and graphitic type (400.7 eV) nitrogen atoms [51]. Additionally to the XPS data, elemental analysis demonstrated the amounts of C, H, N and O (calculated) in the whole sample were about 40.4 wt%, 5.1 wt%, 25.9 wt% and 28.6 wt%, respectively. A schematic representation of the chemical structure of the N-CD is illustrated in Fig. 2c.

The morphological investigation of the N-CD was performed with SEM, AFM and optical microscopy. Fig. S3 (
                           Supplementary Information
                        ) shows transmission-mode SEM images of as-synthesized N-CD deposited by dip-coating onto an ultrathin carbon film supported copper grid (400 mesh). The N-CD sample prepared with this process is composed of quasi-spherical nanoparticles with sizes of less than 50 nm up to ∼ 100 nm, as seen in Fig. S3 (
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). In spite of the low dimensionality of the as synthesized particles, it is known that CD have a tendency to form aggregates in the solid state [52,53]. Thus, to gain further insights of the organization of this material in the films, a dispersion of N-CD in isopropanol was deposited by spin-coating on top of a silicon substrate, which was then placed on a hot plate at 100 °C for 10 min to remove the solvent and mimic the conditions applied during OLED assembly. The AFM image displayed in Fig. 3
                        a reveals that this process led to the formation of N-CD aggregates, which seem to maintain a round shape in the orientation parallel to the substrate surface. The statistical particle size-distribution calculated for 60 particles displayed on this image (see histograms in Fig. 3c) shows an average diameter (x,y plane) around ∼1.06 μm, whereas the average height profile (z plane) was estimated to be ∼ 110 nm. The same sample (deposited by spin-coating and annealed at 100 °C) was analyzed by SEM. The average N-CD particle diameter estimated from SEM image was ∼1.41 μm, using 130 particle aggregates for the count, as can be seen in Fig. S4 (
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). Fig. S5 shows an optical microscopy image of the same sample on a larger scale (0.02 mm, magnification 100X), where the micrometer-sized particle aggregates can be seen. Thus, the dimensions observed for the N-CD were strongly dependent on the processing conditions, and the diameters varied from less than 50 nm (Fig. S3) up to ∼1.41 μm (Fig. S4). Regardless of the impressive size variation, a round shape was observed in all cases in the direction horizontal to the substrate surface. In spite of the low-dimensionality of the N-CD in solution, after deposition, these particles seem to self-assemble in highly anisotropic aggregates, with a much stronger agglomeration trend in the axis parallel to the substrate (diameter/length on the order of microns) compared to the axis perpendicular to the substrate surface (height on the order of ca. 100 nm). To our knowledge, this is the first time that such a behavior is clearly demonstrated for green-emitting N-CD.

The thermal decomposition of the N-CD powder was also investigated. From the TGA curve (Fig. S6, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ), it can be seen that the N-CD were thermally decomposed in three steps. The first mass loss (∼4.5 %) at temperature lower than 120 °C was related to the removal of residual ethanol molecules from the solvent, trapped between the N-CD sheets. The second decomposition process (∼40 %) was observed in a temperature range from 130 °C to 500 °C, due to the pyrolysis of oxygen- and nitrogen-containing functional groups. The major mass loss (∼50 %) was observed in a temperature range from 500 °C to 680 °C and refers to combustion of the carbon skeleton. This analysis was useful to evaluate the thermal stability of the synthesized material and indicates that a temperature of 100 °C should be the limit to thermally treat samples containing the N-CD in order to remove residual solvent and preserve their integrity during application in the OLEDs.

CV was employed to estimate the HOMO/LUMO energy levels of the N-CD (see Fig. S8, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). Based on the voltammograms, the N-CD exhibit an oxidation peak (Eoxid = 1.20 VAg/AgCl) with onset potential (Eoxid,onset) at 0.45 VAg/AgCl. A reduction peak (Ered) was observed at −1.40 VAg/AgCl. The Eg determined from the CV results was 2.60 eV, which is in a good agreement with the value estimated from the optical absorption spectrum (Fig. 4(a); 2.62 eV, λonset = 473.7 nm). The EHOMO of N-CD was calculated using Eq. (1), and the estimated value was −5.05 eV. Then, ELUMO was calculated from the values estimated for EHOMO and Eg, and the obtained value was −2.43 eV. Next, the N-CD were mixed with ZnO at different concentrations and the resulting composites were applied as ETL in blue-emitting PFO-based OLEDs.

In the normalized absorption spectra of the film stacks (glass-ITO|PEDOT:PSS|PVK|PFO|ZnO or ZnO/N- CD(0.1 to 2%)) (Fig. S9a), an absorption band with maxima centered at 385 nm is observed, which was assigned to the electronic absorption of delocalized π orbitals along the PFO chain [59,60]. The normalized PL spectra of the same samples were obtained under excitation λexc = 380 nm (fig. S9b), where the PFO is preferably excited. Each PL spectrum exhibited a characteristic vibronic progression with bands centered at 433 (strong, 0–0), 455 (moderate, 0–1) and 490 nm (weak, 0–2) due to S0 → S1 singlet exciton transition of the PFO film, attributed to a mixture of the PFO crystalline (β-phase) and amorphous (α-phase) phases [60,61]. Overall, the ZnO or ZnO/N-CD(0.1 to 2%) films deposited on top of the PFO emitting layer did not alter significantly the photophysical properties of the PFO polymer (see Fig. S9, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). As general a trend, no signal was detected for the N-CD greenish emission (∼530 nm) in the films, which was related to the low concentration and low intensity of the PL of this material in relation to the PFO signals. However, a low intensity broad signal between 550 and 600 nm was observed in some samples (more visible in the spectra of ZnO/N-CD(0.25%) sample, green line in Fig. S9b), which was attributed to the formation of PFO aggregates [62] and changes in the morphology, although a minor contribution arising from the PL emission of N-CD aggregates cannot be completely ruled out.

Fig. 5
 shows the AFM images obtained on the surface of samples consisting of glass-ITO|PEDOT:PSS|PVK|PFO|ZnO or ZnO/N-CD(0.1 to 2%). It can be seen that the root mean square (RMS) roughness was reduced from 39.1 nm (Fig. 5a) to 36.2 nm (Fig. 5b), 34.5 nm (Fig. 5c) and 37.4 nm (Fig. 5d) after modifying the ZnO with 0.1%, 0.25% and 0.5% of N-CD, respectively. It is expected that the functional groups present on the surface of the N-CD interact with the surface of the ZnO nanoparticles, passivating their defects and improving the contact between the ETL and the emissive layer [42,63]. On the other hand, the RMS roughness increases for the ZnO/N-CD(1%) (RMS = 39.8 nm) and ZnO/N-CD(2%) (RMS = 54.0 nm) samples, due to the larger formation of N-CD aggregates in these films, as seen in the optical microscopy images (see Fig. S10, 
   Supplementary Information
). For comparison, the RMS roughness of the glass-ITO|PVK|PFO film was found to be 62.6 nm (see Fig. S11, 
   Supplementary Information
). Thus, it is evident that the use of ZnO or ZnO/N-CD on top of the PFO emissive layer contributes to smoothen the surface prior to deposition of the Ca/Al counter electrode. We note that the RMS value found for the glass-ITO|PVK|PFO film stack may be considered high for application in OLEDs, but it was estimated from a large scan area of 50 μm × 50 μm, in contrast to the much lower scan areas (between 1 μm × 1 μm and 5 μm × 5 μm) typically reported for these systems. In such a large region, both crystalline and amorphous polymer regions should be present (observed in the PL data as well), reflecting in the overall surface roughness.

In addition to these data, KPFM analyses were performed on the glass-ITO|PVK|PFO, glass-ITO|PVK|PFO|ZnO and glass-ITO|PVK|PFO|ZnO/N-CD(1%) samples, in scan areas of 5 μm × 5 μm (Fig. S12, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). The contact potential difference (CPD) was estimated to be −0.246 V, − 0.186 V and −0.153 V, respectively. The less negative value observed for the sample containing ZnO/N-CD indicate a shift of the surface work function to lower values, which should impact in the charge injection process when these materials are applied in the OLEDs, as will be discussed later.

The OLED containing the neat ZnO film as ETL presented a VON of 4.0 V, Lmax of 432 cd m−2 (at 7.4 V) and current efficiency (ηcurr) of 83.8 mcd A-1 (at 7.0 V), as shown in Fig. 6 (blue curves). We observed a significant improvement in the performance of the diode containing the ZnO/N-CD(0.1 wt%) film (red curves): VON of 3.6 V, Lmax of 581 cd m−2 (at 7.6 V) and ηcurr of 128.8 mcd A-1 (at 7.0 V). In fact, this device delivered the best performance of all the OLEDs investigated. This OLED also showed an intense blue color with chromaticity coordinate (CIE) of (0.146; 0.107). On the other hand, at higher concentrations (>0.5 wt%), N-CD aggregates become more present in the ZnO films, decreasing the performance of the devices (see Fig. S10, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). The OLED containing the ZnO/N-CD(2%) film showed the worst performance: VON of 4.8 V; Lmax of 123 cd m−2 (at 8.6 V); ηcurr of 47.8 mcd A-1 (at 7.6 V) and a blue color with CIE of (0.146; 0.100) (dark cyan curves). All the OLEDs emitted the blue color characteristic of PFO, with little shift in the chromaticity coordinates (see Fig. S13, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ), revealing that the N-CD are not playing a significant role as light-emitters in the OLEDs investigated here. All the EL spectra exhibited the vibronic progression in the blue region, with bands centered at 424 (0–0), 452 (0–1) and 478 nm (0–2). The EL spectral profiles were similar to the PL spectra (see Fig. 6c and Fig. S9b, 
                           Supplementary Information
                        ). The intensity ratio of the 0–1 band and the 0–0 band (I(0−0)/I(0−1) or I(β -phase)/I(
                        α
                        -phase)) was ∼ 1.1 in all the EL spectra, indicating that the deposition of ZnO or ZnO/N-CD films on top of the polymer emitting layer did not change the PFO chain orderliness [64].
